At 1550 GMT, the rand had slipped 1.04% to 14.0250 per dollar following an overnight close of 13.8825. JOHANNESBURG - The rand weakened on Wednesday as traders treaded cautiously ahead of major data releases late this week, with Standard &amp; Poor's the last of three main rating agencies to decide on the country's debt.Stocks booked their fourth straight monthly drop as investors fled risky assets in the wake of resurgent dollar and signs of economic strength in the United States.At 1550 GMT, the rand had slipped 1.04% to 14.0250 per dollar following an overnight close of 13.8825, bringing the month's losses to more than 4%.The rand and other emerging currencies fell after a jobs report from the United States showed a surprise increase in employment, further solidifying bets the Federal Reserve will raise rates next month.The rand began the week on the front foot after Fitch and Moody's affirmed South Africa's investment grade status over the weekend, but has since retreated due to a dollar surge and worries that S&amp;P's may buck the trend and cut the rating to junk.&quot;The market is a bit cautious with a lot of data out on Friday,&quot; said market analyst at IG Group Shaun Murison.&quot;With S&amp;P's it will be close, but it looks like we've done enough to keep our heads above board.&quot;The blue-chip JSE Top-40 index little changed at 43,691, bringing losses for November to nearly 1%. The broader All-share index edged up 0.1% at 50,209.Petrochemical giant Sasol topped the gainers list on the benchmark index, jumping 4.8% to R379.35, tracking a surge in the price of crude oil.Sasol makes fuel from coal and gas but sells at same price as companies that import and refine crude, which climbed more than 7% as the world's largest producers agreed to curb output for the first time since 2008.On the downside, Steinhoff was under pressure, falling 4.3% to R65.44 as the stock started trading without the rights to its next dividend payout.About 242 million shares changed hands, below last year's daily average of 296 million shares.Bonds were mostly flat with the benchmark paper due in 2026 adding 1 basis point to 9.04%.